2. Unbalanced braces or brackets: Every opening brace `{` must have a matching closing brace `}`, and every opening bracket `[` must have a matching closing bracket `]`. Unbalanced braces or brackets can cause parsing to fail.

3. Incorrect quotation marks: JSON requires double quotes `"` for strings and keys. Single quotes `'` are not valid in JSON, and incorrectly placed or mismatched quotes can lead to errors.

4. Data type issues: JSON supports specific data types (string, number, object, array, true, false, null). Entering an unsupported data type or formatting a value incorrectly (like missing quotes around a string) is a common mistake.

5. Trailing commas: JSON does not allow trailing commas after the last element in an object or array. Such commas can lead to parsing errors.

6. Nested structures: Deeply nested objects or arrays might make it harder to spot errors and require careful examination to ensure they are correctly structured.

7. Encoding problems: JSON text should be encoded in UTF-8, and any deviations may cause issues during parsing.
